# BLoC Screen Structure

Every screen that owns a BLoC MUST follow the wrapper/content split inside a **single file**:

- **`SomeScreen`** — `@RoutePage()`, `StatelessWidget`, only provides BLoC(s) and renders content
- **`_SomeScreenContent`** — private widget, all UI logic, `BlocBuilder`/`BlocListener`/`BlocConsumer` live here

```dart
// ✅ GOOD — user_config_example_screen.dart

@RoutePage()
class UserConfigExampleScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  const UserConfigExampleScreen({super.key});

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return MultiBlocProvider(
      providers: [
        BlocProvider(create: (_) => sl<ThemeBloc>()..add(const ThemeStarted())),
        BlocProvider(create: (_) => sl<LocaleBloc>()..add(LocaleStarted(deviceLanguageCode: 'en'))),
      ],
      child: const _UserConfigExampleContent(),
    );
  }
}

class _UserConfigExampleContent extends StatelessWidget {
  const _UserConfigExampleContent();

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return BlocConsumer<ThemeBloc, ThemeState>(
      listenWhen: (prev, curr) => curr.failure != null && prev.failure != curr.failure,
      listener: (context, state) { /* failure handling — see presentation-components.mdc */ },
      builder: (context, state) => Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(title: Text(context.l10n.themeMode)),
        body: ...,
      ),
    );
  }
}

// ❌ BAD — @RoutePage class does UI directly, no content split
@RoutePage()
class UserConfigExamplePage extends StatefulWidget { // ❌ Page suffix
  @override
  State<UserConfigExamplePage> createState() => _State();
}
class _State extends State<UserConfigExamplePage> {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final state = context.watch<ThemeBloc>().state; // ❌ BLoC never provided
    return Scaffold(...);
  }
}
```

## Rules
- `@RoutePage()` goes on the **wrapper only** — never on `_SomeScreenContent`
- Wrapper is always `StatelessWidget` — it never builds UI
- `_SomeScreenContent` can be `StatefulWidget` if local UI state is needed (animations, focus nodes, scroll controllers)
- Initial BLoC events are dispatched in `BlocProvider.create:` — never in `initState` or `build`
- Use `MultiBlocProvider` when the screen owns more than one BLoC

## Do not re-provide BLoCs already in the tree
If a BLoC is already provided by a parent screen or ancestor, just access it via `context.read` / `context.watch`.

```dart
// ✅ GOOD — ThemeBloc provided at app root; child just reads it
class _SomeChildWidget extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    final state = context.watch<ThemeBloc>().state;
    return Text(state.appliedThemeMode.name);
  }
}

// ❌ BAD — re-providing creates a second instance that shadows the parent's
class SomeChildScreen extends StatelessWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return BlocProvider(
      create: (_) => sl<ThemeBloc>(), // ❌ duplicate
      child: ...,
    );
  }
}
```
